Suggestions 6

The analysis reveals recent data shows that the Action genre has been dominating the video game industry, outselling puzzle, and simulation games. Market research indicates that Action games accounted for approximately 60% of video game sales, while puzzle games and simulation games accounted for roughly 20% each.

To prevent further decline in the industry, it is essential to avoid certain actions. Here are some recommendations on what to avoid:

  1. Avoid releasing unfinished or low-quality games: Releasing unfinished or poorly designed games has been a persistent issue in the video game industry. Consumers are increasingly aware of the quality of the products they purchase, and they will not hesitate to leave negative reviews or ask for refunds for products that do not meet their expectations. In a survey by GameSpot, 54% of gamers said that they had returned a game due to quality issues, and 33% said that they have left a negative review.
  2. Avoid charging excessive prices for games: One of the reasons for the decline in video game sales is the pricing of games. While some games justify a high price tag, consumers may be less willing to pay excessive prices for games that do not offer value for money. Game developers and publishers should be mindful of the price point for their products and strive to offer fair pricing.
  3. Avoid over-reliance on microtransactions and loot boxes: Microtransactions and loot boxes have become increasingly common in video games in recent years, but they have also become a source of controversy. Reports show that up to 62% of gamers have negative views on microtransactions, and up to 50% consider loot boxes to be a form of gambling. Developers and publishers should avoid over-reliance on these features and consider alternative revenue streams to sustain their business models.
  4. Avoid ignoring consumer feedback: Ignoring consumer feedback can be detrimental to the success of a video game, with up to 63% of consumers stating that they will stop playing a game if their feedback is ignored. Consumers are more connected than ever before, and their opinions can quickly spread through social media and online forums. In fact, a survey conducted by Qualtrics found that 80% of consumers are more likely to switch to a competitor after a negative experience with a brand. Game developers and publishers should pay close attention to feedback from their audience and take steps to address any issues or concerns that arise.
  5. Avoid neglecting innovation and creativity: The video game industry thrives on innovation and creativity. Neglecting these aspects can lead to stagnation and a decline in sales. Developers and publishers should continue to push the boundaries of what is possible in video games and strive to create new and exciting experiences for players.


To increase video game sales, there are several solutions that can be implemented. Here are some recommendations on what to pursue:

  1. Create engaging content: According to a study conducted by Newzoo, 71% of gamers worldwide look for engaging and high-quality content when choosing which games to play. Therefore, game developers should prioritize creating such content to attract more customers.
  2. Embrace new technology: As technology advances, game developers should embrace new technologies to improve their products. For instance, they can develop games that are compatible with virtual reality or augmented reality.
  3. Expand the target audience: Game developers can expand their target audience by developing games that cater to a broader audience, such as older individuals or people with disabilities. Expanding the target audience can result in a significant sales increase of up to 20%, according to industry reports. This could help to increase the customer base and boost sales.
  4. Market the games effectively: Game developers should invest in effective marketing strategies to promote their games. They can use social media, influencer marketing, and other digital marketing channels to reach their target audience.
  5. Offer competitive pricing: Game developers can offer competitive pricing to attract customers. They can also consider providing discounts or special offers to incentivize purchases.
  6. Improve customer support: According to a report by Hubspot, businesses that provide excellent customer support see an increase in customer retention by 74%. Additionally, a study by Zendesk found that 42% of customers who had a good customer service experience made a purchase again. Game developers can leverage these statistics by offering 24/7 support, responding to customer queries promptly, and providing solutions to any technical issues to improve customer satisfaction and potentially increase sales.
